<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Bossi opens new wounds in coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of Italy's populist Northern League, yesterday
reopened a damaging split in the Italian government by accusing Mr Silvio
Berlusconi, the prime minister, of trying to cut the League out of the
governing coalition.
An agitated Mr Bossi, interviewed on television as he returned from holiday
in Sardinia, also claimed that Mr Berlusconi had asked President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro for permission to hold new elections. The claim was immediately
dismissed by the prime minister and the president.
'I won't waste time denying nonsense,' Mr Berlusconi was reported as saying.
'I'll have to propose a tax on chatter.' The president's press office issued
a statement saying Mr Bossi's claim was 'absolutely without foundation'.
Mr Bossi's comments demonstrate, however, that three weeks' holiday has not
healed the rift between the League leader and his coalition allies.
'It's not possible to offload the League,' Mr Bossi said, pointing out that
it was the principal parliamentary party. 'At this point perhaps we ought to
give Berlusconi an abacus, if he goes on fooling himself that it's possible
to throw out the League before we've passed an anti-trust law or a new
constitution.'
Mr Gianfranco Fini, leader of the third main coalition partner, the
far-right National Alliance, said in a television interview that Mr Bossi's
behaviour was 'puerile'.
At the beginning of August, Mr Berlusconi and Mr Bossi held all-night
discussions to patch up their differences. The next day they appeared on
television together in an attempt to demonstrate to nervous financial
markets and the Italian people that there were no hard feelings between
them, in spite of Mr Bossi's persistent criticism of Mr Berlusconi.
Since then, Mr Bossi has kept up an informal commentary on League policy
from the beach in Sardinia, but has refrained from attacking Mr Berlusconi.
Mr Bossi's intervention could upset financial markets, just as they seemed
to have recovered their poise following the turbulence caused by political
uncertainty and the consequent rise in Italian interest rates last month.
Yesterday, before Mr Bossi's comments were broadcast, the lira strengthened
against the D-Mark and was trading at less than L1,000 for the first time
since August 8.
In recent days, Mr Bossi has been incensed by press reports that he claimed
to have prevented an armed rebellion by League supporters in 1986-87. He has
blamed 'anti-democratic' journalists for misreporting his comments, and has
threatened legal action against television and newspapers for spreading
'disinformation'.
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
