<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Danish Elections: Denmark set for close poll race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Danish government's decision to call a general election on September 21
has put into place the final piece in an unprecedented series of elections
and referendums in the Nordic region this autumn. The Danish vote will come
just three days after Sweden's general election and will be followed in
October and November by referendums in Finland, Sweden and Norway on
European Union entry.
As a member of the EU for two decades, Denmark is playing a bit part in the
Nordic drama, but its election will be hard fought. Voters have an unusually
clear choice between left and right and opinion polls suggest that at
present the result is too close to call.
Mr Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, Social Democrat prime minister, will be hoping that
an expected strong swing to the Social Democrats in Sweden will be mirrored
in Denmark.
He leads a four-party centre-left majority coalition, but opinion polls
suggest its two small centre party members may not win the necessary 2 per
cent of the vote to regain election to the Folketing (parliament). They hold
the balance between the main left- and right-wing blocs, the Centre
Democrats and the Christian People's Party - hence the starker confrontation
than usual between left and right.
The left-wing alternative (known to its opponents as 'the red cabinet') is a
new Social Democrat-dominated government in coalition with the Radical
Liberals, a social-liberal party which is a member of the present coalition.
An SDP-Radical government would have to rely for its majorities in the
Folketing on support from the left-wing Socialist People's Party (SPP).
Fewer inhibitions about high government spending, and an aggressive
environmental policy would be among the hallmarks of a government which
comes came under SPP influence - although its more extreme demands would be
strongly opposed by the Radical Liberals.
The right-wing alternative ('the black cabinet' say its opponents) would be
a coalition of the Liberal and Conservative parties, which formed the core
of the non-socialist governments which held office under Mr Poul Schluter
from 1982 to January 1993.
It offers curbs on welfare programmes, tight control of government spending,
a more favourable income tax regime and measures to make the labour market
more flexible by reducing high unemployment benefits and tightening
eligibility rules for benefit. This government would require the support of
the populist right-wing Progress party, formerly an anarchic maverick
shunned by mainstream parties.
However, it has now become sufficiently respectable for the Liberals and
Conservatives to be openly proposing a government allied with it.
In the economic debate, both right- and left-wing blocs are claiming credit
for Denmark's present relative success. The economy is set to grow this year
by about 4 per cent. There are large surpluses on the balance of payments
accounts, low inflation, and a budget deficit of modest proportions - about
5.5 per cent of gross domestic product. Unemployment is around 12 per cent
but beginning to decline.
Mr Rasmussen is claiming the credit, but the opposition insist it was their
policies between 1982 and 1993 which stabilised the economy and laid the
basis for recovery.
With Mr Schluter replaced as Conservative party leader by the lesser known
Mr Hans Engell, the right-wing charge is now being led by Mr Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen, the Liberal leader who was foreign minister from 1982 to
1993. The Liberals have performed better than the Conservatives in opinion
polls and this year's European parliament election, which makes Mr
Ellemann-Jensen favourite to lead a Liberal-Conservative government.
However, a clear-cut government of either left or right is far from assured.
Voters may yet reprieve the Centre Democrats and the Christian People's
party. That would be in keeping with a long tradition by which small parties
of the centre call the tune in brokering a coalition and the political
choices are fudged.
</TEXT>
<XX>
