<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Profit-taking and 'marking time' were how traders described a poor trading
day in both stock index futures and the traded options, writes Joel Kibazo.
In futures, the September contract on the FT-SE 100 opened at 3,287. This
turned out to be the day's high and the contract drifted lower for the next
few hours. The easier bond prices only served to increase the drift in the
first half and one trader said: 'The contract just cannot seem to shake off
the holiday mood.'
September steadied over the lunchtime period before the dull opening on Wall
Street triggered another retreat in the contract.
September finished at 3,263, down 24 from the previous close and at a strong
premium of 14 points to the underlying cash market. Volume remained very
poor, reaching only 8,333 lots by the close.
In spite of the modest volume, dealers remain positive about the underlying
tone of the market and expect a return to more positive territory in the
near future.
It was also a slow day in the traded options. Total turnover fell to 18,044
contracts, against Friday's figure of 34,796 lots. Among the index options,
the FT-SE 100 saw business of 5,817 lots and the Euro FT-SE 1,591 contracts.
GEC was the busiest stock option, trading 1,304 lots. It was followed by
Barclays with 1,112 contracts.
</TEXT>
