<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / International Company News: American Airlines seeks Dollars
1bn cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
American Airlines yesterday announced plans to reduce its annual expenses by
Dollars 1bn, making it the latest US carrier to embark on a severe
cost-cutting programme in an attempt to ensure long-term profitability.
The big US airlines are suffering from damaging fare wars in their home
market. Last year, AMR, American's parent group, reported a loss of Dollars
110m and recorded total operating expenses of more than Dollars 15bn.
A project to streamline American's headquarters management and
administrative staffs was unveiled yesterday by Mr Robert Crandall,
American's chairman, who said the carrier wanted to reduce annual labour
costs by Dollars 750m and other expenses by Dollars 250m.
Mr Crandall did not provide details on how the savings would be realised,
but said a team of executives would spend the next four to five months
searching for ways to streamline management and staff support functions.
American has been cutting its management wage bill for the past two years,
but believes further job reductions are necessary, both in the management
and union workforce. The key to American's cost-cutting programme, as at
other airlines, lies in negotiating an agreement with employee unions.
The carrier is following other leading US airlines, which have all
instituted programmes to lower their expenses.
In July, United Airlines was acquired by its employees in return for wage
cuts and other labour concessions worth Dollars 4.9bn.
Delta Air Lines recently introduced a plan to carve Dollars 2bn a year out
of its annual operating costs within the next three years, while USAir has
also launched a programme to cut Dollars 1bn in its annual operating costs
within the same period of time.
In spite of traffic growth and low fuel prices, the industry as a whole lost
Dollars 2.1bn last year because airlines were unable to charge fares high
enough to cover costs.
America said yesterday it had proposed wide-ranging changes to its contract
with the Allied Pilots' Association, which expires today.
However, the pilots' union has yet to respond to those proposals.
American also faces arbitration with the flight attendants' union later this
year, which it hopes will yield productivity improvements. It has held
preliminary talks with the union representing mechanics and ground employees
about revising their contract when it becomes due for amendment in March
next year.
The news of American's cost-cutting ambitions lifted the airline's share
price Dollars 1 1/4 to close at Dollars 59 1/2 on the New York Stock
Exchange yesterday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>American Airlines Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4512 Air Transportation, Scheduled.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  Labour.
    MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
