<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Argyll sells 151 small stores to Spar for Pounds 19.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Argyll Group, the UK's third-largest food retailer, has sold 151 of its
smallest Lo-Cost and Presto supermarkets for Pounds 19.7m to a consortium of
five companies operating under the Spar banner.
The deal rids Argyll of most of its Lo-Cost and Presto stores smaller than
4,000 sq ft, allowing it to concentrate on larger stores operating under
those names and on the Safeway superstore chain.
The future of the Lo-Cost discount chain has been under review since May
when Argyll said operating profits in its Presto/Lo-Cost division had fallen
by 20 per cent to Pounds 40.7m in the year to April 2.
Analysts attributed much of the fall to Lo-Cost. It was hit by increased
price competition in the grocery sector, and particularly by the 'Price
Check' campaign launched in May 1993 by the Gateway group, now Somerfield.
Some 123 Lo-Cost and 28 Presto stores are being sold. Fixtures and fittings
and goodwill have been sold for Pounds 10.7m, and Argyll expects to realise
at least Pounds 9m more from property transactions. That would represent a
Pounds 7m profit over the Pounds 12.7m book value of the stores, whose
annual sales are Pounds 150m.
The stores will be converted into Spar convenience stores and all 1,750
staff will be kept on.
'These stores have gone to a natural home, given their size and location,'
said Mr Colin Smith, Argyll's chief executive.
Mr Smith said Lo-Cost had remained profitable. But further evidence of the
pain felt by some discounters was provided by last month's profits warning
from Shoprite, the discount chain operating mainly in Scotland.
The sale leaves Argyll with 144 Lo-Cost stores, of which fewer than 50 are
smaller than 4,000 sq ft. Mr Smith said the trading prospects of the
remaining stores would be kept under review. Argyll is conducting a
strategic review of all its businesses.
The consortium buying the stores includes AF Blakemore, the family-owned
wholesaler; Appleby Westward, the grocery distributor; Alfred Jones; Capper;
and James Hall.
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
