FT  31 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How low can BBC1 sink? It screens a new cringe show today in which a search
will be made for 'Britain's most useless woman'. What disgraceful male
chauvinist piggishness ..Whoops] Sorry, it actually says 'Britain's most
useless man', so that's all right. Called The Opposite Sex the programme is
produced and presented by Chris Tarrant, star 12 years ago of 'OTT', which
stood for 'Over The Top' where people were covered in custard and so on. It
was scrapped by Bob Phillis, then head of Central TV, now Deputy
Director-General of the BBC. Today's show is largely devoted to couples
'airing their dirty laundry in public' (8.30).
The 40-minute drama 'Low Level Panic' in the BBC2 series Stages stars
Charlotte Coleman as one of three flatmates who spend much of the time in
their bathroom (9.25). Desmond Morris ends his series about The Human Animal
with a programme on playfulness (9.30 BBC1). That is followed by two more
repeats from the ATV stockpile: Roger Moore and Tony Curtis as The
Persuaders and Richard Bradford in Man In A Suitcase (10.20).
