<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Ulster Unionist leader accepts Major's pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr James Molyneaux, leader of the Ulster Unionist party, said yesterday he
was confident that the government had no plans to change Northern Ireland's
constitutional position - 'contrary to wild speculation over the weekend'.
The measured tone of his remarks was echoed by Mr John Taylor, UUP MP for
Strangford, who warned against premature reaction by unionists.
But the hardline Democratic Unionist party warned of fresh trouble in the
event of new government concessions.
The Rev Ian Paisley, the DUP leader, angrily demanded a meeting with Mr John
Major, saying a truce based on a British 'surrender' could lead to fresh
strife.
He said: 'Any government that subverts the democratic wish of the people and
goes against all the pledges they have made is going to have a situation
which is a recipe for civil war in Northern Ireland.'
The Ulster MPs' comments came after a statement on Monday night by Mr Gerry
Adams had raised mounting expectations of a ceasefire still higher.
In his first public acknowledgement that he had advised IRA leaders to
consider halting their 25-year armed campaign, Mr Adams said he had always
argued that a 'changed political climate could break the . . . stalemate and
create the potential to eradicate the underlying causes of conflict.
'In my updated assessment to the IRA leadership I expressed my belief that
the current political climate provides that potential.'
