<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Deal may trigger extra US cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
White House officials are now at 'not much less than fever pitch', say
Washington diplomats, over the improved prospects for peace in Northern
Ireland, and members of the US Congress are confident of an IRA ceasefire.
The administration of President Bill Clinton is also considering an aid
package to help buttress a ceasefire, although no details have yet been
worked out.
'There are a number of options to provide aid to Ireland already. We won't
make any decision on what to do until we see exactly what the terms of the
ceasefire are,' said Ms Dee Dee Myers, the White House press secretary, who
was accompanying Mr Clinton on his holiday in the Massachusetts coastal
resort of Martha's Vineyard.
Congressional aides said any request for more money to accompany a peace
agreement would probably receive considerable support, but that no specific
package was yet circulating for discussion.
The US currently gives Dollars 20m (Pounds 12.9m) a year to the
International Fund for Ireland, which is jointly administered by the UK and
Ireland.
Some members of Congress criticised the appropriation each year, on the
grounds that the fund seemed less deserving than some developing countries
whose aid has been cut. But no substantial opposition is expected, even for
a much larger sum, if there seems a real prospect of peace in Northern
Ireland.
The US also allowed a veteran Irish republican activist into the country
yesterday on a special visa as hopes for a breakthrough rose.
Mr Joe Cahill, a founding member of the Irish Republican Army who was
reprieved in 1942 after being sentenced to death for killing a policeman,
arrived in New York yesterday after Mr Clinton personally approved a request
for a waiver from immigration laws that would otherwise have excluded him
because of past terrorist activities.
The visa is the first the Clinton administration has granted to an Irish
republican since the row over the visit in February of Mr Gerry Adams. US
officials were disappointed then by Mr Adams's failure to renounce violence.
Hopes for a ceasefire have risen in the US after the visit to Ireland last
week of a delegation headed by Mr Bruce Morrison, a former congressman with
close ties to the Clinton administration. Mr Morrison, although expected to
report to the White House, stressed he was not an official representative of
Mr Clinton.
</TEXT>
