<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Japan's jobless at seven-year peak of 3%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japanese unemployment rose to a seven-year high of 3 per cent in July -
nearly 1.9m people - casting a shadow over an already weak economic
recovery.
The second monthly increase in a row, from 2.9 per cent in June, increases
the chances the jobless rate will break through its 1987 record of 3.1 per
cent. The job situation will remain 'severe' even if the general economy
picks up, warned Mr Kozo Igarashi, chief cabinet secretary.
This increases the pressure on the coalition government, led by Mr Tomiichi
Murayama, a Socialist, whose chances of lifting its low popularity depend on
delivering an economic recovery.
Japanese unemployment remains low by comparison with 6.1 per cent in the US,
yet any rise provokes a fresh round of public agonising over Japan's ability
to uphold the hallowed tradition of job stability. Corporate Japan's drive
to cut costs, by shifting production to cheaper locations in south-east Asia
and cutting domestic recruitment, are the main features of the increase in
jobless.
Tokyo economists do not believe the unemployment rate will significantly
surpass 3 per cent, yet this latest rise is enough to worry the government.
Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto, minister of international trade and industry,
yesterday called for the creation of more temporary posts, helped by fewer
official restrictions on personnel agencies. Mr Manso Hamamoto, labour
minister, promised to boost efforts to help the jobless back to work.
The number out of work rose sharply, by 18.2 per cent over the year to July,
to 1.88m. Of those in work, the number of salaried employees fell by 20,000,
for the first time in 16 years, a mark of corporate cost cuts.
At the same time, the overall labour market has weakened, the main reason
for the government's gloom over the outlook. There were only 62 jobs
available for every 100 people seeking work in July, the third consecutive
monthly decline.
This confirms the poor job outlook for the latest batch of university
graduates, which accounts for most job seekers. The job seekers' ratio
stands at the lowest since January 1987, when the economy was reeling, as
now, from a rise in the yen. A further decline in the ratio is expected, Mr
Dick Beason, senior economist at James Capel Pacific, says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
