<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Polly Peck case shooting arrests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkish police arrested four men yesterday in connection with the shooting
of an executive from Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the UK administrators for Mr Asil
Nadir's collapsed Polly Peck conglomerate. Istanbul police held two men
suspected of the shooting of Mr David Adams on August 19 in Istanbul, and
arrested two more for ordering the shooting. Police caught a 21-year-old
youth taking part in another Istanbul shooting on August 25 and tracked down
the others after questioning him. Mr Adams, a Briton, is a Coopers
management consultant but has no link to the Polly Peck case. Coopers said
they believed the real target was Mr Christopher Howell, a partner in the
firm and the executive in charge of the Polly Peck case. Mr Howell was
beaten up by two Turks on June 7, the night before a Turkish court addressed
criminal charges against the Polly Peck administrators resulting from
complaints made by Mr Nadir.
