<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Setback for Cyprus solution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
United Nations efforts to end the 20-year-old division of Cyprus were dealt
a further blow yesterday when Turkey endorsed a motion by the Turkish
Cypriots formally abandoning the search for a federal solution. Already
smarting at legal moves by the European Union to block the import of
Turkish-Cypriot produce, and EU support for the Greek-Cypriot application to
join the Union, the parliament of the self-declared Turkish-Cypriot republic
passed a motion on Monday to co-ordinate foreign, defence and security
policy with Ankara, in effect endorsing the fact of partition and supporting
the aspiration of formal integration with Turkey. Turkish officials describe
the motion as similar to existing security arrangements between Athens and
the Greek Cypriots.
</TEXT>
