<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hungarian police have arrested two nationals trying to sell 2kg of
radioactive material, believed to be uranium fuel rods from the former
Soviet Union. Agents of Hungary's intelligence services had trailed the two
suspects outside the country before detaining them in a Budapest hotel
carpark on Monday as they sought to sell the material for Dollars 40,000 per
kg. The incident comes amid international concern that nuclear material may
be finding its way out of Russia to help other countries or terrorist groups
make atomic weapons. The Germans have made four seizures of illegal
weapons-grade plutonium and uranium since May that Bonn believes may have
come from former Soviet stocks in Russia.
