<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Warning on German growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COLOGNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German economy is clearly growing faster than could have been expected
at the beginning of the year, but there are grounds for concern, said Mr
Tyll Necker, head of the Federation of German Industry. Mr Necker said he
agreed in the main with the forecast published on Monday by the Organisation
for Economic Co-operation and Development, which said it expected the German
economy to grow 1.8 per cent in 1994. He said he saw a pattern common to
German recoveries, with exports picking up first, then capital goods, and
lastly a recovery in employment and consumer spending. The economics
minister, Mr Gunter Rexrodt, this month raised the government's forecast of
1994 growth from 2.0 to 2.5 per cent. But Mr Necker said increases in taxes
and other administrative costs expected in 1995 could pose additional
economic burdens that could choke off the recovery.
