<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Renault sale waits on Volvo: Government to remain majority
shareholder, says Balladur
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French government will press ahead with the partial privatisation of the
Renault motor group as soon as Volvo agrees, Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime
minister, said yesterday. The Swedish car-maker owns 20 per cent of Renault.
Full-scale negotiations with Volvo will begin as soon as the French
authorities have completed a valuation of Renault, which is estimated to be
worth around FFr40bn (Pounds 4.8bn). Mr Balladur, speaking on French radio,
sketched a scenario in which Volvo would sell all or part of its 20 per cent
holding at the same time as the government sold a portion of its 80 per cent
stake.
However, he stressed that the state would remain the majority shareholder'
of Renault 'at least for the present', thereby quashing speculation that it
might be tempted to reduce its holding to a blocking minority of 38 per
cent. 'Have you ever heard me say that I intended to privatise 100 per cent,
or even 60 per cent, of Renault? Never, never,' he said.
Mr Balladur emphasised that he saw the partial privatisation and the
reduction of Volvo's stake as a precursor of the formation of new
international alliances for Renault within the motor industry. Renault and
Volvo were originally intended to forge such an alliance until the Swedish
company's shareholders torpedoed the scheme last December.
The two groups have since been searching for ways of unravelling their
cross-shareholding agreement. Volvo is reported to be willing to reduce its
20 per cent stake to 8 per cent, in return for the French company's 45 per
cent holding in its truck business.
Analysts yesterday speculated that the French government may be aiming to
complete Renault's partial privatisation before the end of November, when
the present 'divorce' agreement with Volvo is due to expire.
Meanwhile, Assurances Generales de France (AGF), the French insurance group
which is another contender for privatisation, will today publish its results
for the first half of 1994.
AGF was originally expected to unveil its interim figures later in the
autumn, but is believed by analysts to have accelerated the announcement in
the hope of enhancing its privatisation prospects. It is expected to
announce a fall in net profits to between FFr1bn and FFr1.2bn from FFr1.4bn
in the first half last year.
Volvo results, Second section front page
