<HEADLINE>
FT  31 AUG 94 / Invasion of Haiti edges a step closer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES HARDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US and Caribbean governments yesterday moved closer to launching a
multinational invasion force against Haiti, as the United Nations warned
that diplomatic efforts to oust the military leadership had failed.
Momentum for a military coalition grew when Jamaica, Barbados, Belize and
Trinidad-Tobago indicated they would commit a small number of troops to a
Haiti force. The Bahamas, Guyana and Antigua are also considering joining.
The Caribbean countries' decision is a victory for the US, which wants at
least symbolic contingents from allies to move in behind an initial wave of
US troops. The four nations will supply a total of about 266 soldiers as
part of a force estimated by US officials at about 10,000.
They announced their backing at a meeting of the Caribbean Community
(Caricom) in Kingston, Jamaica, attended by Mr Strobe Talbott, US deputy
secretary of state, and Mr John Deutch, deputy defence secretary.
'The time for action has arrived,' Mr Deutch said. 'There can be no doubt in
anybody's mind that the multinational force is going to Haiti.'
Another senior US official said that the US was not yet at the point of
invasion 'but we are moving briskly in that direction. . . We are very close
to exhausting all peaceful means'.
The US won a UN mandate last month to use 'all necessary means' to oust the
military elite who deposed President Jean-Bertrand Aristide three years ago.
In New York, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary-general, said the last
peaceful efforts to persuade Haiti's rulers to step down had failed as 'the
military people in Haiti refused to talk with my special representative'. He
said there were no plans to continue the diplomatic mission unless there was
a new mandate from the Security Council.
Mr Boutros Ghali implied the next step would be up to the US. The Security
Council or the group of states who 'sought the mandate. . . will have to
take their own decision', he said.
The stepping up of US rhetoric follows criticism that the Haiti issue had
been put on the back burner as the Cuban refugee crisis gripped the
attention of the Clinton administration. But the US on Monday reiterated the
'determination of the international community to take all the necessary
means to bring the early restoration of democracy'.
Mr Deutch said training for the multinational force was expected to begin
immediately at a military base in Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
