<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / NHS union scorns pressure to curb claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and Financial Times Reporters
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Royal College of Nursing yesterday became the first health service union
to indicate that it would use the pay rise of 4.7 per cent awarded to MPs as
a basis for its own next claim.
The college, traditionally one of the most moderate of public-sector unions,
said it would reject any government attempt in the coming pay review to
revive last year's pressure for 'an exceptionally modest increase'.
Mr Christopher Cordwell, a senior member of the college's industrial
relations team, said on BBC radio: 'Nurses have clearly delivered more
productivity by measures the government have themselves set down over the
last few years, and we expect that to be noted by the review body.
'The Royal College of Nursing has no problem with MPs being properly
rewarded, but against such a background, what we don't expect is the
government to repeat the pressure it exerted on the review body last year.'
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, said it was
unfair for MPs to be awarded pay rises well above the rate of inflation
while workers in the public sector were expected to show restraint.
He said on BBC radio: 'If they are going to make these silly rules let them
keep them themselves.'
Doctors will step up opposition to proposals for performance-related pay in
the National Health Service at a special conference in London tomorrow, Alan
Pike writes.
The British Medical Association has called representatives from every
hospital in the country to the meeting. They are due to discuss an issue
that is bringing the medical profession into renewed confrontation with the
government.
Ministers have said a shift from the NHS's centralised pay structure to
locally determined performance pay must start this year. Mr Alan Langlands,
NHS chief executive, has written to local managers of hospitals and other
services telling them to prepare plans for the change by October, and have
local machinery in place by February.
The BMA regards the timetable as 'impractically short' and the principle of
performance pay as 'totally inappropriate to the work of the medical
profession'.
A BMA briefing paper, circulated to its local negotiating committees in
advance of the conference, says that performance-related pay for hospital
doctors would lead to increased emphasis on financial objectives, resulting
in a greater focus on the number of patients treated rather than the quality
of care.
