<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / BMA gathers opponents of pay reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Doctors will step up opposition to proposals for performance-related pay in
the National Health Service at a special conference in London tomorrow.
The British Medical Association has called representatives from every
hospital in the country to the meeting. They are due to discuss an issue
that is bringing the medical profession into renewed confrontation with the
government.
Ministers have declared that a shift from the NHS's centralised pay
structure to locally determined, performance-based pay must start this year.
Mr Alan Langlands, NHS chief executive, has written to local managers of
hospitals and other services telling them to prepare plans for the change by
October, and have local pay machinery in place by February.
The BMA regards the timetable as 'impractically short' and the principle of
performance pay as 'totally inappropriate to the work of the medical
profession'.
This week's conference will seek to set the BMA's opposition in the context
of wider public-sector concerns about the weakening of centralised pay
structures. Representatives of both the Police Federation and the First
Division Association, the senior civil servants' union, will address the
meeting.
A BMA briefing paper, circulated to its local negotiating committees in
advance of the conference, says that performance-related pay for hospital
doctors would lead to increased emphasis on financial objectives, resulting
in a greater focus on the number of patients treated rather than the quality
of care.
It says: 'Local performance pay could be used by hospital managers to
pressurise consultants into compliance with the hospital's business needs -
for example giving greater priority to the patients of GP fundholders, or
doing a larger number of minor operations rather than more serious cases
which might generate less money for the hospital.'
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, has said that local pay
arrangements would encourage and promote good clinical practice.
</TEXT>
