<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / Brazil inflation plan setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's anti-inflation plan, launched in July, suffered its first serious
setback yesterday when the government's main inflation index showed a
smaller than expected fall. The index, the IPC-R, showed inflation at 5.46
per cent for the four weeks to August 15, compared to 6.08 per cent in the
previous four-week period. The index appears to have remained high because
of rent increases and a lower than expected drop in clothing prices. The
government sought to play down the figure, claiming it contained 'one-off
factors' and pointing out private sector indices showed monthly inflation
has fallen to about 2 per cent. But the IPC-R is the main index the
government uses to judge pay awards. The August figure will be used to
attack Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, former finance minister, who engineered
the anti-inflation plan. He leads polls for October's presidential elections
mainly because electors credit him with taming Brazil's inflation, which
reached 50 per cent in the month before the plan's launch.
