<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / Russian government battles with farmers on grain prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A battle over grain prices is growing between the Russian government and
farmers as this year's grain harvest draws to a close. Officials yesterday
forecast that the harvest would reach between 90m and 100m tonnes.
For the first time since the collectivisation of Russian agriculture, the
government is buying grain from its own producers at market rates rather
than at a state price.
But grain producers are balking at what they complain are prohibitively low
prices and warn that impoverished farms may be unable to bring in the
harvest in some regions.
Mr Nikolai Rybakov, a manager at Roskhlebprodukt, the state grain purchaser
which was transformed into a joint stock company, said yesterday that the
government had bought about 2m tonnes of grain so far, just half of the
amount bought by the end of August last year.
Roskhlebprodukt's granaries are not filling up because farmers are lobbying
to persuade the government to buy their grain at the 'indicative price' of
between 200,000 and 220,000 roubles (Dollars 93 and Dollars 102) a tonne
agreed by the regional government officials and producers in the spring. But
Roskhlebprodukt is, for the first time, trying to operate like a private
company.
'We look at the rates in regional commodities markets and then we decide
what price to pay farmers,' Mr Rybakov said. He said that Roskhlebprodukt
had been paying between 90,000 and 180,000 roubles a tonne of grain, 'but we
cannot pay farmers more than the world prices'.
Some regional authorities warn that Moscow's financial austerity could
jeopardise the harvest. Agriculture officials in the east of the country
said that because of a shortage of fuel and spare parts only 55 per cent of
the crop had been harvested.
But the Russian government, struggling to keep inflation in check, appears
determined to face down the farmers.
Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, the prime minister, warned farmers in central Russia
at the weekend that the state would not pay more than world prices for
grain. If farmers refused to sell at these prices, he cautioned, the
government 'is buried under more favourable offers from foreign grain
producers'.
His tough statements came two days after farmers demonstrated in Moscow to
protest at the government's 'criminal destruction of Russian agriculture'.
</TEXT>
