<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Political correctness can have the oddest effects. Today BBC2 champions
apartheid and screens a programme singing the praises of prostitution. If
the network presented a series promoting new comedians provided they were
white and excluded blacks there would be hell to pay. But The Real McCoy is
okay because it promotes black comedians and excludes whites. Why this South
African style 'separate development' for different races, so vehemently
opposed by BBC2 types for decades, is now acceptable on BBC2 itself is
anybody's guess (10.00).
BBC2 would not, of course, allow a woman to make a programme arguing that
prostitution can be fun because, as we know from the commissars of political
correctness, prostitution exploits women. But it seems that male
prostitution is altogether different. Just as BBC2 has, for some years,
found space for the homosexually erotic while toeing the suppression line on
the heterosexually erotic, so Open Space is readily given over to an
explanation of how 'prostitution can be a positive and enjoyable choice'
provided you are homosexual (11.15).
</TEXT>
