<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / Levers hold up Railtrack's ambitions: The company can only
go so far in opening lines during the strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack's efforts to open longer sections of the British railway network
on strike days seem set to slow down as the company reaches the limits of
signalling technology.
By concentrating staff at the most modern computer-controlled signalboxes
Railtrack has in recent weeks managed to open up sections of track way out
of proportion to the number of signalworkers employed.
At first sight the numbers are hard to credit. Just 600 signalling staff -
13 per cent of the normal workforce of 4,600 - allowed Railtrack to open up
40 per cent of its network in last week's 24-hour strike.
But unless striking members of the RMT transport union return to work in
large numbers Railtrack will face serious problems in opening up its more
labour-intensive lever-operated signal boxes.
Railtrack has inherited three generations of railway signalling technology
from British Rail.
No fewer than 951 of the 1,125 signalboxes on the railway's 10,000-mile
network date from the steam age. They need a signalman to pull a lever to
change the signal.
A further 165 are panel boxes introduced in the 1960s. These consist of
large display panels where a red light records the passage of a train along
the track and where the signalling staff push buttons to operate the
signals.
The latest signalling boxes are known as integrated electronic control
centres. Signals are controlled by computer, although the signal worker can
override the computer if a train breaks down or if there is any other
disruption to the normal schedule.
Railtrack has only nine of these control centres but they control extensive
lengths of track.
Railtrack has managed to open a disproportionately large part of its network
by three main methods.
It has allocated its signalling staff to the more modern electronic and
panel boxes where they control greater lengths of track.
Railtrack's Great Western zone, which operates 1,370 miles of track from
London Paddington to the West Country and south Wales, has only eight panel
boxes on the 225 miles from London to Plymouth but 11 manual boxes on the 80
miles from Plymouth to Penzance.
It has concentrated its efforts on the panel boxes and maintained a 'near
normal' mainline service down to Plymouth but no trains onwards to Penzance
on strike days.
This approach is typical of Railtrack zones around the country. They have
shut down branch lines which depend on the manual boxes and kept open the
main routes. Cutting out the branch line services simplifies the railway
timetable and means fewer trains crossing over the main lines.
Secondly, by reducing the frequency of many of its services there are
greater intervals between trains so a smaller number of signalling staff can
run the railway safely.
Finally, although Railtrack says it has been running 40 per cent of its
network, this claim is only true if it is applied to peak and daytime
operations. Services are generally starting later than normal and closing
earlier in the evening, so fewer signalworkers are needed on shift duty.
The uneven distribution of the new and old technology boxes around the
country has sometimes prevented Railtrack from opening up through routes.
The east coast main line linking London King's Cross with Edinburgh has
electronic control centres at Newcastle upon Tyne and York and panel boxes
at King's Cross, Peterborough and Doncaster.
But the middle stretch of line between Peterborough and Doncaster has a
number of level crossings controlled by manual boxes. For the first 10 weeks
of the strike Railtrack could open the northern and southern sections of the
line but was unable to provide a through service.
As BR has modernised its network it has brought in more electronic control
centres. The Chiltern line is controlled from one box at London Marylebone
and has maintained a near normal service.
In the longer term, Railtrack is looking to bring in even more advanced
technology which will do away with trackside signals and the wires which
link them. Drivers will have in-cab display panels linked by radio to
control centres telling them the state of the track ahead.
The 550-mile west coast main line, to be modernised over the next few years,
could be controlled by one signal box.
The traditional signal worker seems set to go the same way as the fireman
who stoked the steam engine.
</TEXT>
