<HEADLINE>
FT  30 AUG 94 / Fifth of companies 'expect to relocate': Survey shows
Bristol, Edinburgh and Nottingham are favourites while London is placed 18th
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than a fifth of UK companies expect to relocate in the next five years,
with Bristol, Edinburgh and Nottingham the top three choices for businesses
planning a move, says a survey published today.
Wigan, Sunderland, Bradford, Liverpool and Belfast were the least popular of
the 40 cities considered. London ranked 18th behind Manchester, Birmingham,
Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
The survey, by Black Horse Relocation, part of Lloyds Bank, and Management
Today magazine, received responses from chairmen, chief executives and other
senior directors of 536 companies. Ten companies had turnovers of more than
Pounds 100m and four employed more than 5,000 staff.
About 22 per cent said they were very likely or quite likely to relocate in
the next five years. More than a third cited business expansion as the main
reason for moving.
The survey says: 'This was nearly twice as important as restructuring or
reorganising businesses which was the next most popular reason, chosen by 16
per cent.'
Mr John Carolan, managing director of Black Horse Relocation, said: 'This is
a clear sign that the economy is recovering and is very encouraging for the
future. Previously most companies have been moving because they have been
cutting back or closing works.'
Black Horse expects to move about 4,500 families this year on behalf of
companies and public-sector organisations.
The most important factors in choosing a business location, according to the
survey, were:
Quality of the local workforce (identified by 57 per cent of executives who
responded in the survey).
Quality of road communications (44 per cent).
Cost of overheads, such as local authority rates (36 per cent).
Also important were availability of local customers (23 per cent); property
costs (21 per cent) and competitive wage rates (20 per cent). Executives
were less concerned about access to London (6 per cent) and proximity to air
and rail networks (5 per cent).
Most important personal factors cited by executives included: overall
quality of life (57 per cent); cost of living (30 per cent); crime rate (29
per cent); access to countryside (27 per cent); and the quality of local
schools (26 per cent).
Bristol was found to be the most attractive centre for business relocation,
closely followed by Edinburgh and Nottingham. Norwich, Plymouth and Exeter
were among those in the top 10.
</TEXT>
